"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512659","Home Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>Ministerial discussions continue to take place at EU meetings on implementation of the EU-Turkey deal.</p><p>More detailed discussions at official level are taking place with Greece on a regular basis. These are ensuring that the deal is carried out in accordance with all international and EU law including human rights safeguards.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-18T16:14:44.843Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512659/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512659/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-13","Turkey: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has had discussions with her Greek counterpart on the implementation of human rights safeguards for refugees under the EU-Turkey deal.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","33717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512660","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-20","<p>During 2014, DFID did not disburse Official Development Assistance to any country for cultural and arts projects.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-04-20T14:08:39.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512660/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512660/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-13","Overseas Aid: Culture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department spent on cultural and arts projects overseas in 2014.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","33847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512661","Department for International Development","false","2016-04-20","<p>Improving access to education and the quality of learning for all children – especially those who are most disadvantaged - is a priority for the Department. The UK supported 11 million children in school between 2010 and 2015. We have again committed to support 11 million children in the poorest countries gain a decent education by 2020. Having children in school and learning enhances economic growth and contributes to better governance, peace and democracy.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-04-20T16:34:29.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512661/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512661/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-04-13","Developing Countries: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to widen access to education in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","33873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512662","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-22","<p>Information about the number of appeals (a) heard against school exclusion and (b) how many were found in favour of the appellant is published by the Ministry of Justice in the Tribunals and Gender Recognition Statistics Quarterly. The most recent statistics for the First-tier Tribunal SEND are for the period 1 September 2014 to 31 August 2015, published on 10 December 2015, which can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015</a>.</p><p> </p><p>These statistics cover the years 2011/12 to 2014/15.</p><p> </p><p>The statistics for earlier years can be viewed at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/385777/sen-tables-2014.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/385777/sen-tables-2014.xls</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","33878","2016-04-22T13:57:38.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512662/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512662/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-13","Tribunals: Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeals against school exclusion were heard at the First Tier Tribunal (SEN and Disabilities) in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","33877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512663","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-22","<p>Information about the number of appeals (a) heard against school exclusion and (b) how many were found in favour of the appellant is published by the Ministry of Justice in the Tribunals and Gender Recognition Statistics Quarterly. The most recent statistics for the First-tier Tribunal SEND are for the period 1 September 2014 to 31 August 2015, published on 10 December 2015, which can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2015</a>.</p><p> </p><p>These statistics cover the years 2011/12 to 2014/15.</p><p> </p><p>The statistics for earlier years can be viewed at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/385777/sen-tables-2014.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/385777/sen-tables-2014.xls</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","33877","2016-04-22T13:57:38.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512663/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512663/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-13","Tribunals: Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeals against school exclusions at the First Tier Tribunal (SEN and Disabilities) were upheld in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","33878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512664","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-22","<p>We want prisons to be places of hard work, rigorous education and high ambition, with incentives for prisoners to learn and for prison staff to prioritise education and employment opportunities.</p><p> </p><p>We already work with a wide range of employers in prison through One3One Solutions and engagement by Prison Governors. But we want Governors to do more so we are putting the tools to drive this change in the hands of those at the frontline who best know what works.</p><p> </p><p>We are keen to increase the number of employers who can provide valuable vocational work for offenders while in prison and who are able to offer them support in preparation for release and employment opportunities following their release. I regularly meet businesses across the country, to encourage them to get involved and new businesses are now coming on board as a consequence. The Employers Forum for Reducing Reoffending brings together employers willing to employ offenders and provides a range of advice and support to new employers considering working with offenders and provides business to business mentoring to members of the Forum. We are working with the Department for Work and Pensions to increase the involvement of more businesses. The Prime Minister has also announced changes to recruitment practises across the civil service to ensure that people are considered on their merits and not on their criminal conviction and we want to encourage more employers to do the same.</p><p> </p><p>Separately, the Secretary of State for Justice has commissioned a review of prison education led by Dame Sally Coates.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-04-22T13:57:40.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512664/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512664/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-13","Offenders: Rehabilitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent steps his Department has taken to ensure that ex-offenders are helped into work or education upon the completion of their sentence.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","33940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512665","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-27","<p>The Channel Islands and the Isle of Man enjoy special arrangements for access to the EU, provided under Protocol 3 to the UK’s Treaty of Accession to the European Community. As set out in the Government’s White Paper: ‘The process for withdrawing from the European Union’, published on 29 February, the withdrawal process is unprecedented. There is uncertainty about how it would work. There would be no requirement under EU law for these arrangements to be maintained if the UK left the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government respects and values the constitutional relationship between the UK and the Crown Dependencies, and will continue to engage constructively with them to address issues and areas of concern.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","33932","2016-04-27T14:38:32.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512665/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512665/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-13","UK Membership of EU: Crown Dependencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 9 March 2016 to Questions 30551 and 30552, on UK membership of EU: Crown Dependencies, what his Department's policy is on the future of the principles enshrined in Protocol 3 should the UK vote to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","33933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512666","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-27","<p>The Channel Islands and the Isle of Man enjoy special arrangements for access to the EU, provided under Protocol 3 to the UK’s Treaty of Accession to the European Community. As set out in the Government’s White Paper: ‘The process for withdrawing from the European Union’, published on 29 February, the withdrawal process is unprecedented. There is uncertainty about how it would work. There would be no requirement under EU law for these arrangements to be maintained if the UK left the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government respects and values the constitutional relationship between the UK and the Crown Dependencies, and will continue to engage constructively with them to address issues and areas of concern.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","33933","2016-04-27T14:38:32.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512666/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512666/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-13","UK Membership of EU: Crown Dependencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 9 March 2016 to Questions 30551 and 30552, on UK membership of EU: Crown Dependencies, if his Department will take steps to ensure that the principles underlying those arrangements are not affected in the event that the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","33932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512667","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer to PQ 20357.</p><p> </p><p>Incidents involving drones are rare, but we remain constantly vigilant to all new threats to prison security. This Government has made it a criminal offence to throw, or otherwise project, any article of substance into prison without authorisation. Anyone using drones in an attempt to get contraband into prisons can be punished with a sentence of up to two years. We take a zero tolerance approach to illicit material in prisons and work closely with the police and CPS to ensure those responsible for a drone incident are caught and, if appropriate, prosecuted.</p><p> </p><p>There were no reported drone incidents in 2013; 2 reported incidents in 2014; and 33 reported incidents in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>These figures include drone finds and sightings of drones by prison staff in and around all types of public and private prisons in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><p>These figures have been drawn from live administrative data systems. Care is taken when processing and analysing the returns, but the detail collected is subject to the inaccuracies inherent in any large scale recording system.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T14:44:44.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512667/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512667/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-13","Prisons: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents involving the use of drone technology have been recorded at each type of prison facility in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","33806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512668","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Organ Donor Register is a confidential record maintained by NHS Blood and Transplant and patient details are not shared with other organisations; asking prisoners if they are registered could serve to compromise their confidentiality. Joining the Organ Donor Register is a voluntary matter and there are no plans to focus on specific groups such as prisoners. The decision to be a donor is one which prisoners should discuss with their next of kin.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains fully committed to the strategy agreed in 2013 “<em>Taking Organ Transplantation to 2020” </em> (<a href="http://www.nhsbt.nhs.uk/to2020/" target="_blank"><strong>www.nhsbt.nhs.uk/to2020/</strong></a>) which aims to enable the UK to match world-class performance in organ donation and transplantation.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T15:05:52.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512668/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512668/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-13","Prisoners: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 13 April 2016 to Question 33183, whether his Department advises prisons (a) to ask prisoners upon induction if they are already organ donors or if they wish to become one and (b) to keep records of which prisoners are registered organ donors; and if he will amend prison service orders to ensure that the organ donors register is taken into account if a prisoner dies in a prison or in a hospital.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","33792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512669","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The MoJ’s contract with Capita Translation and Interpretation (TI) naturally expires on 30<sup>th</sup> October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry does not anticipate an early withdrawal of services by Capita; no financial penalties are therefore currently applicable.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-18T12:52:08.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512669/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512669/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512669/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-13","Interpreters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what financial penalties Capita is obliged to pay under its contract with his Department for leaving its contract to provide interpreting services.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","33807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512670","Leader of the House","false","2016-04-18","<p>A Family Test was introduced by the Government in 2014 – it aims to bring a family perspective into policy making. It will ensure that impacts on family relationships and functioning, both positive and negative, are recognised in the process of policy development and help inform the policy decisions, and any subsequent legislation, made by Ministers.</p><p> </p><p>The Test is not a ‘tick box’ or ‘pass v fail’ exercise, it is about thinking carefully how new policy can support or potentially undermine family relationships. Policy is always about trade-offs but the Family Test ensures family considerations are explicitly considered and recognised when making those trade-offs.</p><p> </p><p>While the guidance encourages publication, there is no requirement to do so.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2016-04-18T15:33:49.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512670/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512670/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-04-13","Legislation: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, pursuant to his oral contribution of 10 March 2016, Official Report, column 444, whether he expects primary and secondary legislation to be subject to the family test and the results published.","false","Biography information for Mr David Burrowes","Enfield, Southgate","Mr David Burrowes","33911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512671","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government takes the illegal movement of dogs and puppies seriously and it is committed to working with the Devolved Administrations, delivery bodies, enforcement agencies and non-government organisations to tackle this issue.</p><p> </p><p>While I have had no discussions with local authorities in Northern Ireland about the illegal trafficking of puppies into Scotland, the Defra Chief Veterinary Officer has recently discussed the issue with his Scottish, Welsh and Northern Ireland counterparts. Additionally, there have been discussions on this issue between other Defra officials and officials within the Devolved Administrations.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not carried out an assessment of the impact of transferring Trading Standards search powers to local port authorities in Scotland as this is a devolved matter. However, Defra will continue to work closely with the Scottish Government and other interested parties to ensure that there is a full exchange of ideas and information on combating the illegal importation of puppies.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-04-18T09:42:18.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512671/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512671/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-04-13","Dogs: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with local authorities in Northern Ireland about the illegal trafficking of puppies into Scotland; and what assessment she has made of the effect on such trafficking of the transfer in Scotland of search powers from Trading Standards to local port authorities.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","33909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512672","Prime Minister","false","2016-04-20","This is new money provided by the Treasury. It will be spent on bringing together some of the most sophisticated technology, experts and resources to tackle money laundering, tax evasion and wider forms of financial crime anywhere in the world.","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-04-20T14:21:33.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512672/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512672/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-04-13","Tax Havens","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, with reference to his Oral Statement of 11 April 2016, Official Report, column 26, on the Panama Papers, from which departmental budgets the Government plans to draw the resources to support the new cross-agency taskforce to analyse the information that has been made available in those papers.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","33898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512673","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Strategic Defence and Security Review made a commitment to “integrate infrastructure policing further and to review the options to do this” and this review is underway.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-21T11:56:04.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512673/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512673/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-13","Infrastructure: Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to establish an Infrastructure Police Force to replace the Civil Nuclear Constabulary, British Transport Police and Ministry of Defence Police.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","33881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512674","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The number of traffic officers employed by Highways England is shown in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TOS - Grade</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p><strong>1720</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p><strong>1673</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p><strong>1602</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p><strong>1513</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p><strong>1425</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p><strong>1446</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p><strong>1439</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T16:07:32.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512674/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512674/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Traffic Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Highways England traffic officers were employed on 15 March (a) 2016, (b) 2015, (c) 2014, (d) 2013, (e) 2012, (f) 2011 and (g) 2010.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","33760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512675","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The median and mean wages levels for male and female employees are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Median wage</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Organisation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Male</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Female</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DfT(c)</p></td><td><p>£45,747</p></td><td><p>£42,103</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Network Rail</p></td><td><p>£33,781</p></td><td><p>£32,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Highways England</p></td><td><p>£24,054</p></td><td><p>£27,455</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HS2 Ltd</p></td><td><p>£51,552</p></td><td><p>£38,928</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Office of Rail and Road</p></td><td><p>£58,152</p></td><td><p>£40,900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency</p></td><td><p>£19,155</p></td><td><p>£19,155</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency</p></td><td><p>£25,328</p></td><td><p>£25,162</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Vehicle Certification Agency</p></td><td><p>£36,565</p></td><td><p>£25,758</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Mean wage</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Organisation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Male</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Female</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DfT(c)</p></td><td><p>£51,012</p></td><td><p>£45,335</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Network Rail</p></td><td><p>£36,789</p></td><td><p>£36,073</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Highways England</p></td><td><p>£31,608</p></td><td><p>£30,974</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HS2 Ltd</p></td><td><p>£65,130</p></td><td><p>£44,650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Office of Rail and Road</p></td><td><p>£56,597</p></td><td><p>£45,445</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency</p></td><td><p>£22,197</p></td><td><p>£20,649</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency</p></td><td><p>£26,108</p></td><td><p>£24,826</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Vehicle Certification Agency</p></td><td><p>£36,798</p></td><td><p>£25,918</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The central Department and its Agencies have historically had differences in mean and median pay levels of male and female staff. In 2014, pay, terms and conditions were modernised, including shortening the lengths of pay ranges. As a result of this, and the 2015 pay strategy, the differences in mean and median pay levels of male and female staff have decreased. The central Department and its Agencies are committed to continuing to reduce the differences over the next few years.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-18T14:55:44.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512675/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512675/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Department for Transport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) median and (b) mean wage is of (i) male and (ii) female employees of (A) his Department, (B) Network Rail, (C) Highways England, (D) HS2 Ltd, (E) the Office of Rail and Road, (F) the DVLA, (G) the Driver Vehicle Standards Authority and (H) the VCA on the latest date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","33761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512676","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government supports choice for consumers, and wants to see both taxis and private hire vehicles prosper.</p><p> </p><p>The Mayor, Transport for London (TfL), the police and local authorities have a range of tools available to them to seek to address any concerns they may have over the safety or performance of taxi and/or private hire vehicle services. Effective use of these tools allow both licensed taxi and private hire vehicles to operate lawfully and meet the demands of London’s travelling public.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T15:27:34.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512676/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512676/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Taxis: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking in conjunction with the Mayor of London to safeguard the licensed taxi trade; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","33726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512677","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government attaches a high priority to passenger safety in the licenced taxi and private hire vehicle trade. The legislation that provides for the licensing of private hire vehicle services aims to safeguard passengers by ensuring that drivers and vehicles that are fit for purpose. This legislation allows local licensing authorities the discretion to set standards they deem appropriate for their area. To help with this, the Department has issued best practice guidance.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T15:24:07.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512677/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512677/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512677/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Taxis: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what priority the Government attaches to passenger safeguarding in the licensed taxi and private hire vehicle trade; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","33725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512678","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>My department has 4 contracts with IBM (UK) Ltd and details are contained in the table below</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Agency</p></td><td><p>Purpose of contract</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DfTc</p></td><td><p>Annual Software maintenance on IBM SPSS licensing for statistical analysis</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DVLA</p></td><td><p>Q Radar Security Monitoring Tool</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DVLA</p></td><td><p>IBM Software-Extended Support</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DVLA</p></td><td><p>IBM Enterprise Licensing Agreement (ELA)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-18T14:58:45.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512678/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512678/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Department for Transport: IBM","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what contracts IBM currently holds with his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","33749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512679","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government is determined to meet the requirements set out in the Ambient Air Quality Directive and to do so in the shortest time possible. As set out in the recent National Air Quality Plan, the Government intends and expects that the UK will be fully compliant by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>Any decision regarding future airport capacity will take into account the Government’s Air Quality Plan and its commitment to comply with EU air quality limit values.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-18T13:45:54.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512679/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512679/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512679/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Airports: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if the Government will make it its policy not to permit any airport expansion that would worsen air quality in an area where breaches to current or likely future air quality limits are already anticipated or where there is a significant risk of such expansion causing breaches to current or likely future limits.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","33752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512680","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The majority of public funding for local bus services is via block grant provided to local authorities in England from the Department for Communities and Local Government. However, since 2014, my Department has also provided around £40m of Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) funding directly to English local authorities each year to help deliver bus services.</p><p> </p><p>Details of BSOG grant allocations for previous years are published in tables on the GOV.UK website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/search?q=Bus+Service+Operators+Grant" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/search?q=Bus+Service+Operators+Grant</a></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T15:31:49.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512680/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512680/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Bus Services: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department provided in bus subsidies to each local authority in England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","33756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512681","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-22","<p>Although Support for Maritime Training (SMarT) has a fixed budget, funding continues to be allocated on the basis of demand. The figures below therefore reflect the level of demand for rating to officer conversion training and for ratings training – both of which have been met in full.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Rating to Officer Conversion Training</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Expenditure £</p></td><td><p>% of SMarT Budget</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>15,879</p></td><td><p>0.13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>9,649</p></td><td><p>0.06</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>23,998</p></td><td><p>0.16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Ratings Training</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Expenditure £</p></td><td><p>% of SMarT Budget</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>6,594</p></td><td><p>0.055</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1,270</p></td><td><p>0.008</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2,056</p></td><td><p>0.014</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>As in previous years, £100,000 has been earmarked to train ratings and for rating to officer conversion training for each year between April 2014 and March 2016. Demand for this training has been very low and the allocation has not been used. The shortfall in demand for ratings training may still be due to the evident preference for Apprenticeship training rather than the traditional route.</p><p> </p><p>The SMarT budget was increased from £12 million to £15 million per annum from April 2014 and is reflected in the percentage figures from 2014-15 onwards.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","33740","2016-04-22T12:18:01.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512681/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512681/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Shipping: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funds were available to employers from the Support for Maritime Training (SMarT) budget for rating to officer conversion training in each year since 2013-14; what proportion of that budget was spent in each such year; and what proportion of the total SMarT budget that amount represented in each such year.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","33739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512682","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-22","<p>Although Support for Maritime Training (SMarT) has a fixed budget, funding continues to be allocated on the basis of demand. The figures below therefore reflect the level of demand for rating to officer conversion training and for ratings training – both of which have been met in full.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Rating to Officer Conversion Training</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Expenditure £</p></td><td><p>% of SMarT Budget</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>15,879</p></td><td><p>0.13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>9,649</p></td><td><p>0.06</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>23,998</p></td><td><p>0.16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>Ratings Training</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Expenditure £</p></td><td><p>% of SMarT Budget</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>6,594</p></td><td><p>0.055</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>1,270</p></td><td><p>0.008</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2,056</p></td><td><p>0.014</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>As in previous years, £100,000 has been earmarked to train ratings and for rating to officer conversion training for each year between April 2014 and March 2016. Demand for this training has been very low and the allocation has not been used. The shortfall in demand for ratings training may still be due to the evident preference for Apprenticeship training rather than the traditional route.</p><p> </p><p>The SMarT budget was increased from £12 million to £15 million per annum from April 2014 and is reflected in the percentage figures from 2014-15 onwards.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","33739","2016-04-22T12:18:02.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512682/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512682/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Shipping: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding was available to employers from the Support for Maritime Training (SMarT) budget for trainee seafarer ratings in each year since 2013-14; what proportion of the budget was spent in each such year; and what proportion of the total SMarT budget that amount represented in each such year.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","33740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512683","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>Highways England is responsible for litter clearance on all sections of the M23. It carries out regular inspections to monitor the state of the network and to ensure that they are complying with Environmental Protection Act regulations.</p><p> </p><p>Mid Sussex District Council is responsible for litter picking the A23 trunk road, with the exception of the section between Hooley to Central London which is the responsibility of Transport for London.</p><p> </p><p>Regular meetings between Highways England and the council are held to establish the most appropriate ways to keep the road clear of litter. We are currently agreeing a new framework for working jointly to share traffic management nationally which should be in place in Mid-Sussex and the South East by early June.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England has also set up a liaison group with Surrey County Council and other authorities to look at ways to prevent litter being discarded on our highways and roads.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-18T15:15:04.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512683/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512683/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","A23 and M23: Litter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to (a) prevent and (b) collect litter and waste on the A23/M23.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","33833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512684","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-22","<p>I welcome the publication of the Office of Rail and Road's (ORR’s) recommendations in March this year following Which?'s super-complaint into passenger compensation. It is vital that customers who suffer delays or cancellations understand their rights to compensation and have access to it in a timely way. Industry must now do much more to make the process quick and user-friendly. We are already working with the Association of Train Operating Companies and the ORR to bring about improvements, and my Department will respond to the ORR’s report in the summer of 2016.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-22T12:21:17.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512684/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512684/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Railways: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that users of the rail network are aware of the compensation schemes available to them when their trains are delayed or cancelled.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","33934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512685","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Department is in the early stages of developing its approach to exploring options on the potential sale of the Government’s shares. No decision has been made on how it will realise value from its stake in NATS.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-18T15:02:19.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512685/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512685/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","National Air Traffic Services: Government Shareholding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 1.302 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress his Department has made on exploring the sale of the Government's 49 per cent shareholding in the National Air Traffic Service.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","33920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512686","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The evacuation safety risk referred to in the Office of Rail and Road’s Board meeting on 22 September 2015 relates to evacuation from a class 700 new Thameslink train in the Snow Hill Tunnels within the Thameslink core section. The Office of Rail and Road has since confirmed that this is a matter for the London Fire Brigade to consider. Both Network Rail, the infrastructure operator, and Govia Thameslink Railway, the Thameslink train operator, have met with the Fire Brigade to discuss the matter. We understand that the London Fire Brigade is content with the measures that have been put in place.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-04-18T16:03:44.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512686/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512686/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Thameslink Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page two of the minutes of the Office of Rail and Road's board meeting on 22 September 2015, what the Govia Thameslink class 700 evacuation safety risks are that are referred to in those minutes.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","33921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512687","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-22","<p>We have regular meetings with the Mayor of London and discuss a range of topics including the Private Hire Vehicle trade.</p><p> </p><p>The respective standards between taxis and private hire vehicles are a matter for the Mayor and Transport for London (TfL). The TfL Board recently approved a number of reforms to the private hire vehicle regulations, including more robust insurance requirements.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-22T12:28:42.99Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512687/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512687/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-13","Taxis: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the Mayor of London about proposals to improve passenger safety and insurance regulations for the private hire vehicle trade.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","33858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512688","Wales Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>Wales Office Ministers have not had any recent discussions with the Children’s Commissioner for Wales about aligning her powers with those of the Children’s Commissioner for England.</p><p> </p><p>The Children’s Commissioner for Wales fulfils an important role in our efforts to protect children and I would of course be happy to meet with her if she feels her role and remit could be strengthened in any way.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-04-18T09:38:45.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512688/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512688/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-04-13","Children's Commissioner for Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the Children's Commissioner for Wales about aligning her powers with those of the  Children's Commissioner for England.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","33829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512689","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-18","<p>The requested information is available from 2015/16 to 2020/21 in the table below.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Forecast number of State Pension recipients (Great Britain and Overseas) by gender: 2015/16 – 2020/21</strong></p><p><br><strong>Recipients of State Pension (thousands)</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong> Men</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Women </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>5,523.1</p></td><td><p>7,399.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>5,648.6</p></td><td><p>7,274.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>5,765.3</p></td><td><p>7,118.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>5,850.8</p></td><td><p>6,956.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019/20</p></td><td><p>5,822.0</p></td><td><p>6,844.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2020/21</p></td><td><p>5,804.7</p></td><td><p>6,794.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br><em>Source: Budget 2016 medium term forecasts</em></p><p> </p><p>Projections beyond 2020/21 will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>These numbers include State Pension claimants living in Great Britain or Overseas.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-18T15:58:00.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512689/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512689/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-13","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the number of (a) men and (b) women who will be in receipt of the state pension in each of the next 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","33798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512690","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-22","<p>This information is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-22T08:45:55.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512690/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512690/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-13","Jobseeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of people receiving jobseekers allowance were reported as having failed to turn up for job interviews in the last year.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","33870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512691","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-21","<p>The information requested is not readily available, and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-21T13:38:41.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512691/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512691/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-13","Housing Benefit: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many families comprised of foreign nationals are claiming housing benefit in the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","33869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512692","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-18","<p>The employment rate for 16 to 64 year olds within the UK is 74.1 per cent; this is based on the latest available figures from the Labour Force Survey covering the period of November 2015 to January 2016.</p><p> </p><p>A measure of those people in contact with mental health services who are 'experiencing enduring and severe mental health issues' is not available as a description to identify this group is not currently defined.</p><p>On 15 February, the Prime Minister announced that tens of thousands of people with mental health conditions will be supported to find or return to work. Action will be taken across government, the NHS and private companies to treat potentially debilitating mental health conditions early on through improved access to care and to help those already struggling with mental health issues to find or return to work.</p><p> </p><p>The new approach is based on recommendations from the Mental Health Taskforce which set out a comprehensive plan to tackle the problem and which recognised clear links between work and good mental health and the need for more people to be able to access treatment early on so they can avoid long-term unemployment.</p><p> </p><p>DWP secured over £115m, including at least £40 million for a health and work innovation fund to pilot new ways to join up across the health and employment systems, in addition to existing £43m for a range of mental health trials.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-18T15:31:17.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512692/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512692/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-13","Employment: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the employment rate is for (a) the general population and (b) people experiencing enduring and severe mental health issues who are being supported by specialist mental health services.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","33903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512693","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-18","<p>Figures for 31 March 2016 are not yet available.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-18T14:10:53.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512693/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512693/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-13","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much Child Support Agency schemes arrears as at 31 March 2016 are being handled by the Child Maintenance Service; and how many cases those arrears relate to.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","33765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512694","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-22","<p>Such information as is available on Personal Independence Payment (PIP) clearances by type (e.g. awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) for both new claims and reassessed claims (for those previously in receipt of Disability Living Allowance (DLA)) is available at Great Britain, Regional, Parliamentary Constituency and Local Authority level, and is published on Gov.UK: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on PIP statistics, including PIP award rates for both new claims and reassessed claims by geography, can also be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-independence-payment-statistics</a>.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-22T12:12:36.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512694/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/512694/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-13","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people previously in receipt of disability living allowance have had an application for a personal independence payment refused following transition from that allowance to such payments in (a) Easington, (b) the North East and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","33775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513781","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","400,000 people have already opened a Help to Buy: ISA to buy their first home. At Budget 2016 the Chancellor also announced a Lifetime ISA which can be used by people under 40 to save for their first home and retirement.","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-19T15:47:41.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513781/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513781/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Owner Occupation and Personal Savings","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to support (a) people with savings and (b) home ownership.","false","Biography information for Nigel Mills","Amber Valley","Nigel Mills","904555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513782","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","The Government wants low taxes, but taxes that are paid. We are cutting corporation tax to 17%, the lowest rate in the G20, reducing the business rates burden in England by £6.7bn over 5 years, and acting on avoidance to ensure a level playing field for all businesses.","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-04-19T13:45:27.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513782/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513782/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Business: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal steps he is taking to support businesses.","false","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","904554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513783","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>At Budget 2016 the Government increased the personal allowance to £11,500 and raised the higher rate threshold to £45,000 in 2017-18.</p><p> </p><p>31 million people will pay less tax after these changes, with a typical basic rate taxpayer paying over £1,000 less income tax in 2017-18 than in 2010-11.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-19T15:41:18.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513783/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513783/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal steps he is taking to help people keep more of their earnings.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","904552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513784","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer I gave to the Hon Member for Richmond (Yorks) during Treasury oral questions on 19 April 2016.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-04-19T13:34:39.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513784/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513784/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Business: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal steps he is taking to support businesses.","false","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","904556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513785","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>Latest figures from the Office for National Statistics show that in the three months to January, Real Average Weekly Earnings grew 2 percent compared to a year earlier.</p><p> </p><p>Wage growth has outstripped inflation for 16 consecutive months. And the OBR forecast wages to grow faster than inflation in each of the next five years.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-04-19T13:23:57.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513785/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513785/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Average Earnings and Inflation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what comparative assessment he has made of trends in the level of wage growth and inflation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","904551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513786","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer that the Chancellor gave to the Hon Member for Bethnal Green and Bow (Ali Rushanara) during Treasury oral questions on 19 April 2016.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-19T14:33:13.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513786/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513786/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Tax Havens: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on requiring multinational companies to disclose to the public the profits they hold in tax havens (a) in British Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies and (b) elsewhere.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","904557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513787","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>At Budget 2016 the Chancellor committed £4.5 million from banking fines to help establish a Helicopter Emergency Medical Service for Northern Ireland, following a bid from the ‘Air Ambulance Northern Ireland’ charity, who will be the ultimate recipient of the funding. The Treasury is currently working with the charity and the Northern Ireland Executive to ensure that this critical lifesaving service is up and running as soon as is practically possible</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-04-19T13:40:36.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513787/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513787/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Air Ambulance Services: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether funding for an air ambulance in Northern Ireland announced in the Budget 2016 will be provided to Air Ambulance NI or the Northern Ireland Executive's Department of Health, Social Security and Public Safety.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","904561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513788","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","400,000 people have already opened a Help to Buy: ISA to buy their first home. At Budget 2016 the Chancellor also announced a Lifetime ISA which can be used by people under 40 to save for their first home and retirement.","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-19T15:44:44.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513788/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513788/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513788/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Owner Occupation and Personal Savings","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to support (a) people with savings and (b) home ownership.","false","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher","904558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513789","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Budget confirmed that the government will aim to deliver more frequent revaluations. A discussion paper setting out options to deliver this was published last month and can be found on gov.uk. I would encourage those who may be effected to make their views known.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-04-19T13:27:43.81Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513789/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513789/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-13","Non-domestic Rates: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to reform the valuation of business rates.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","904553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511258","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>The number of vacancies on the `Find an Apprenticeship` website has been increasing from 71,060 in 2010/11 to 200,460 in 2014/15. The data does not reflect all vacancies as some employers choose alternative methods for advertising their apprenticeship opportunities.</p><p> </p><p><em>English Apprenticeships: Our 2020 Vision</em> sets out our plans to work with providers and employer organisations to reach our commitment of 3 million apprenticeships by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The new Apprenticeship Delivery Board will encourage more businesses to develop quality apprenticeships. Members act as apprenticeship champions within their sector, working with employers of all sizes to increase both the number of apprenticeship places on offer and the supply of talented candidates.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-18T15:13:52.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511258/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511258/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Skills Funding Agency data release of 5 April 2016, what discussions he has had with (a) education and training providers and (b) employer organisations on recent reductions in the number of apprenticeship vacancies.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","33482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511259","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>Latest data shows that the number of vacancies posted on the ‘Find an Apprenticeship’ website have increased each year from 71,060 in 2010/11 to 200,460 in 2014/15. The data does not reflect all vacancies as some employers choose alternative methods for advertising their apprenticeship opportunities.</p><p> </p><p>We are working closely with the Department for Work and Pensions to ensure that jobseekers are aware of apprenticeship vacancies. Vacancies posted on the ‘Find an Apprenticeship’ website are visible to jobseekers on Universal Jobmatch.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-18T15:22:21.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511259/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511259/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in the Department for Work and Pensions on steps to tackle recent reductions in the number of apprenticeship vacancies.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","33483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511260","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Data Protection Act 1998 (DPA) confers a number of rights on individuals in respect of the processing of their personal data by UK organisations. Subject to certain exemptions, section 7 of the DPA gives individuals the right to request a copy of information which an organisation holds about them. An individual can exercise this right, commonly known as ‘subject access’, by making a written subject access request to the organisation.</p><p> </p><p>If an individual would like to find out what information Thomson Reuters holds about them in World-Check, they can email <a href="mailto:contact@world-check.com" target="_blank">contact@world-check.com</a>. Further information about individuals’ rights concerning the processing of their personal data by Thomson Reuters Accelus can be found on their website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://risk.thomsonreuters.com/world-check-privacy-statement" target="_blank">https://risk.thomsonreuters.com/world-check-privacy-statement</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-18T13:12:15.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511260/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511260/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-12","Public Service: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what provisions there are to enable UK citizens to check whether their names and data are held on the World Check database operated by Thomson Reuters Accelus; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","33492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511261","Department for Education","false","2016-04-22","<p>Academy trusts are subject to a more rigorous accountability regime than other types of schools, including the production of annual audited accounts that allow us to identify and act upon irregularity more quickly.</p><p>The Education Funding Agency has found one instance of where the head teacher has been paid more than the publicly disclosed salary in each of the last 3 years. The additional payments were in respect of chief executive or accounting officer responsibilities.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-22T13:53:32.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511261/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511261/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511261/answer/previousversion/55895","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2016-04-12","Headteachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many academy schools have been found to have paid the head teacher at such schools more than the publicly disclosed salary in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","33486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511262","Department for Education","false","2016-04-18","<p>Local authorities are responsible for the oversight of the schools they maintain and carry out their own programmes of financial monitoring.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-18T16:32:14.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511262/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511262/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511262/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-12","Headteachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many LEA schools have been found to have paid the head teacher at such schools more than the publicly disclosed salary in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","33487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511263","Department of Health","false","2016-04-20","<p>No such assessment has been made; the Department assesses the impact of all proposed measures before making legislation using standard government methodology. These Impact Assessments are scrutinised by the Regulatory Policy Committee before publication alongside the Statutory Instrument.</p><p>An assessment of the impact of the provisions introduced by the EU Tobacco Products Directive will be published alongside the implementing Tobacco and Related Products Regulations 2016 in spring this year. The expected health benefits from improved smoking quit rates have been estimated at around £13 billion.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","33481","2016-04-20T13:48:25.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511263/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511263/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-12","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of users of e-cigarettes who will return to smoking tobacco (a) in the year ending May 2017 and (b) in each year between May 2017 and the end of this Parliament as a result of the introduction of the EU Tobacco Products Directive.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","33480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511264","Department of Health","false","2016-04-20","<p>No such assessment has been made; the Department assesses the impact of all proposed measures before making legislation using standard government methodology. These Impact Assessments are scrutinised by the Regulatory Policy Committee before publication alongside the Statutory Instrument.</p><p>An assessment of the impact of the provisions introduced by the EU Tobacco Products Directive will be published alongside the implementing Tobacco and Related Products Regulations 2016 in spring this year. The expected health benefits from improved smoking quit rates have been estimated at around £13 billion.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","33480","2016-04-20T13:48:25.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511264/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511264/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-12","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of users of e-cigarettes who will return to smoking tobacco in the 12 months after the introduction of the EU Tobacco Products Directive.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","33481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511265","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","Since August 2014 there have been 820 polygraph examinations conducted on sex offenders on licence in the community.","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-18T12:26:00.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511265/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511265/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511265/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-12","Sexual Offences: Lie Detectors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on how many occasions a lie detector test has been used for serious sex offenders as part of their licence conditions, upon completion of their custodial sentence, since August 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","33485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511266","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-18","<p>The information requested could only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the number and success rates of PIP appeals in general is published in the Tribunal and Gender Recognition Certificate Statistics Quarterly. The most recent report, for the period October to December 2015, published on 10 March 2016, can be viewed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunal-and-gender-recognition-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunal-and-gender-recognition-statistics-quarterly-october-to-december-2015</a>.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-04-18T15:16:18.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511266/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511266/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511266/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-12","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March 2016 to Question 27711, on personal independence payments appeals, where information on the proportion of people successfully appealing ineligibility for the enhanced rate of mobility under personal independence payments is held.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","33484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511267","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-20","<p>Across all compensation schemes (EU ETS, CPS, RO &amp; FiT) to date, we have paid out over £189m in compensation.</p><p>Of this, the steel sector has been paid over £80m.</p><p>Since 25 Nov 2015, the aluminium sector has been paid over £464,000.</p><p>Additionally, we are processing 2016 EU ETS/CPS claims, as well as RO/FIT compensation applications, so the amounts will increase significantly in coming months.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-20T16:30:57.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511267/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511267/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511267/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Energy Intensive Industries: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much compensation has been paid to (a) all energy intensive industries, (b) the steel industry and (c) the aluminium industry under the energy intensive compensation scheme since 25 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","33509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511268","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>The analysis underpinning the UK Government’s position on the EU Emissions Trading System has considered the impact on the competitiveness of those sectors that compete in the same markets such as construction. We continue to engage proactively with industry as Phase IV discussions continue and welcome any research or evidence on the competitiveness impacts.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-18T12:10:28.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511268/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511268/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511268/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Construction: EU Emissions Trading Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect on the competitiveness of different construction materials competing in the same downstream markets of the EU Emissions Trading System.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","33524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511269","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government recognises the potential of Big Data and is taking steps to ensure the UK is at the forefront of research and innovation in this field.</p><p> </p><p>Figures are only available from 2011, and since that time, the Government has invested over £520 million in developing the UK’s big data and high-performance computing capital infrastructure.</p><p> </p><p>This includes major investments in specialist centres such as the Alan Turing Institute, the Farr Institute of Health Informatics Research, the Higgs Centre for Innovation, and the Hartree Centre at the Daresbury Science &amp; Innovation Campus.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-18T16:37:57.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511269/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511269/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511269/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what funding his Department has provided for big data projects in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","33534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511270","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>We want to give employers in England flexibility in how they use levy funds to pay for apprenticeship training that meets their needs. We know that some employers want to direct their funding to other employers, for instance their suppliers. We will consider ways this could be accommodated whilst avoiding additional complexity, maintaining the aims of the system and remaining compatible with State aid rules.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-18T16:45:51.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511270/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511270/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511270/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether employers will be able to direct unused funds from their apprenticeship levy accounts towards supporting training apprentices working with (a) their distributers and (b) other companies in their supply chain.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","33612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511271","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>I have <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-29/24897/" target="_blank">replied</a> to my hon Friend.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-18T14:36:19.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511271/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511271/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511271/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2016 to Question 31461, when he plans to respond to Question 24897, tabled on 29 January 2016 by the hon. Member for East Worthing and Shoreham for answer on 3 February 2016.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","33635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511272","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Institute for Apprenticeships Board will be appointed through a public appointments process. The outcome will be announced as soon as the process allows in 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-18T15:07:03.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511272/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511272/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511272/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Institute for Apprenticeships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will appoint a Shadow Board of the Institute of Apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","33699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511273","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Office for National Statistics (ONS) provides data on the labour productivity of the Manufacturing, Production and Service sectors between 1990 and 2015. These are presented as levels relative to 2012 and offer both output per worker and output per hour measures.</p><p> </p><p>The ONS data is copied below and can also be found on the ONS website.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-18T15:04:55.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511273/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511273/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the productivity level was in (a) manufacturing and (b) non-manufacturing jobs in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","33703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511274","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-18","<p>We rigorously assess each application on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria. A licence will not be granted if to do so would breach these Criteria.</p><p>Since March 2015 no export licence applications have been refused due to non-compliance with Criterion 2, although seven have been refused under Criterion 7 (risk of diversion to undesirable end users or end use).</p><p>Information on military and dual use export licences is published as Official Statistics in the quarterly and annual reports on Strategic Export Controls which are all available to view on GOV.UK. These reports contain detailed information on export licences issued, refused or revoked, by destination, including the overall value, type (e.g. Military, Other) and a summary of the items covered by these licences.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-18T09:39:15.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511274/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511274/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511274/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-12","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many export licence applications made since March 2015 related to the supply of equipment to Saudi Arabia have not been approved due to non-compliance with criterion 2 of the National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","33665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511275","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>Overseas travel costs for the Anti-Corruption Champion will be included in the next Cabinet Office annual report and accounts, which will be published on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> in due course.</p><p>There were no costs incurred by the Cabinet Office for the Anti-Corruption Champion in the latest annual report and accounts published. Any costs covered by the Cabinet Office for the Anti-Corruption Champion will be included in the next report which will be published on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> in due course.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","33685","2016-04-19T09:38:06.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511275/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511275/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/511275/answer/previousversion/55807","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-12","Anti-corruption Champion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 11 April 2016 to Question 32149, on what page in the Cabinet Office annual report and accounts the specific costs incurred by the Government's Anti-Corruption Champion are set out.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","33684"
