ssioned by the Government; how many man-hours such work represented; if he will estimate the costs of their work; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","33451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509977","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-14","<p>The government published a revised set of government consultation principles in January 2016. These principles give clear guidance to government departments on conducting consultations. The consultation principles state that consultations should last for a proportionate amount of time, and that officials should judge the length of the consultation on the basis of legal advice and taking into account the nature and impact of the proposal. Information is not held on EU consultation recommendations.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-04-14T10:24:16.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509977/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509977/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509977/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) UK and (b) EU recommended minimum time is for government consultations.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","33446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509978","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-18","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my response to the hon. Member for Harwich and North Essex of 14 April 2016.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-04-18T10:10:15.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509978/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509978/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509978/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to his Department's press release of 6 April 2016, entitled Government responds to public desire for EU facts, if the Government will provide a detailed budget breakdown for the digital promotion and website costs associated with the campaign aimed at helping the public make an informed decision in the forthcoming EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","33396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509979","Home Office","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Security Service's historic files on Horst KOPKOW were made available to the public at The National Archives in March 2004 (reference numbers KV2/1500 and KV2/1501). KOPKOW also appears in a report on a file at The National Archives relating to the Gestapo that was made available in February 2005 (reference number KV3/109). None of the files held in The National Archives on Horst KOPKOW are closed. Any redactions made to these files have been made for reasons of national security. The Government is committed to releasing historical files to the National Archives where it is appropriate to do so.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-04-22T11:47:35.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509979/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509979/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509979/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509979/answer/previousversion/55159","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-11","Horst Kopkow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which of the security service files in the series KV2/1500 held in the National Archives on SS Sturmbannführer Kriminaldirektor Horst Kopkow are closed; and for what reasons such files are closed.","false","Biography information for Mr Keith Simpson","Broadland","Mr Keith Simpson","33282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509980","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>The table below sets out how many and what proportion of permanent officials in my Department resigned in each of the last six years.</p><p>Year Headcount % of Workforce</p><p>10/11 43 2.6%</p><p>11/12 32 1.8%</p><p>12/13 48 2.5%</p><p>13/14 56 2.6%</p><p>14/15 48 2.1%</p><p>15/16 76 3.5%</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-19T09:30:36.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509980/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509980/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509980/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","Cabinet Office: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of officials of his Department resigned in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","33284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509981","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer of 14 April 2016, to the hon. Member for Harwich and North Essex.</p><p>All leaflets will be delivered in advance of the 28 day restricted period, beginning on 27 May 2016. The costs of the leaflet will be met from the Cabinet Office budget.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","33273","2016-04-14T15:34:57.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509981/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509981/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509981/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the press release, Government response to public desire for EU facts, published on 6 April 2016, how much and in what areas the Government has spent on the production of its leaflet on the EU referendum; and from which departmental budget that funding has been obtained.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","33272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509982","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer of 14 April 2016, to the hon. Member for Harwich and North Essex.</p><p>All leaflets will be delivered in advance of the 28 day restricted period, beginning on 27 May 2016. The costs of the leaflet will be met from the Cabinet Office budget.</p><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","33272","2016-04-14T15:34:57.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509982/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509982/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509982/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the press release, Government response to public desire for EU facts, published on 6 April 2016, whether the Government plans to complete the delivery of the leaflets on the EU referendum and remove the website, eureferendum.gov.uk, prior to the start of the purdah period related to that referendum on 27 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","33273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509983","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-14","<p>Details of Ministerial meetings with proprietors, editors and media executives are published routinely, and can be found on Gov.uk.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-14T10:22:52.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509983/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509983/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509983/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","Cabinet Office: Corporate Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many events hosted by newspaper proprietors (a) the Prime Minister has and (b) members of the Cabinet have attended in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","33303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509984","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-18","<p>Criminal proceedings connected to the subject matter of the Leveson Inquiry, including the appeals process, have not yet completed. We‎ have always been clear that these cases must conclude before we consider Part 2 of the Inquiry.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-18T08:42:59.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509984/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509984/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509984/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-11","Culture, Practices and Ethics of the Press Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made on part two of the Leveson Inquiry.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","33304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509985","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-20","<p>The leaflet has been made available on Gov.uk and is compatible with assistive technology, and in hard copy in English and Welsh. An audio version and large print version are also available on Gov.uk. CDs of the audio version are being sent to those that are not able to access the website. A braille version will be available on request.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-04-20T15:58:35.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509985/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509985/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509985/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans the Government has to make its leaflet on continuing membership of the EU accessible to people with (a) learning, (b) visual and (c) other disabilities.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","33330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509986","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-14","<p>The hon. Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip is not a Minister attending Cabinet, but attends political cabinet meetings. He is not paid a Ministerial Salary.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-14T10:25:25.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509986/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509986/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509986/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-11","Boris Johnson","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the hon. Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip is paid in his capacity as a Minister attending Cabinet.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","33360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509987","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Government published distributional analysis to accompany Budget 2016 which shows that spending is focused towards households with children and young people, who will receive around £1,500 more per person per year in 2019-20 than working age households without children or young people.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-04-19T14:24:12.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509987/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509987/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509987/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Young People: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure young people are not disproportionately affected by reductions in government expenditure.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","33321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509988","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-14","<p>The government conducted an initial sale of RBS shares in August 2015, raising £2.1bn for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The proceeds from sales contribute to reducing UK government debt.</p><p> </p><p>Further sales will be conducted subject to market conditions, in order to maximise value for the taxpayer. The returns on the government’s interventions in RBS will be determined by the success of the whole of the selling programme, rather than the terms achieved on the first few disposals.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-04-14T14:14:46.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509988/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509988/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509988/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on the public purse of the sale of the Government's remaining RBS shares.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","33260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509989","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-18","<p>A report was generated from the department’s data management system for the financial years requested. I can confirm that a total of 541 officials have resigned in the last six financial years. The proportion of resignations for each of those six years can be viewed in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>April 10 to March 11</p></td><td><p>April 11 to March 12</p></td><td><p>April 12 to March 13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Resignations</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>104</p></td><td><p>82</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Proportion of Officials (%)</p></td><td><p>6.9%</p></td><td><p>9.0%</p></td><td><p>7.2%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>April 13 to March 14</p></td><td><p>April 14 to March 15</p></td><td><p>April 15 to March 16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Resignations</p></td><td><p>83</p></td><td><p>101</p></td><td><p>79</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Proportion of Officials (%)</p></td><td><p>7.5%</p></td><td><p>9.1%</p></td><td><p>6.3%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-18T13:56:44.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509989/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509989/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509989/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Treasury: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of officials of his Department resigned in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","33297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509990","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>The Chancellor has not recently received any specific representations about possible revisions to the seafarer’s earnings deduction.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-19T16:30:13.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509990/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509990/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509990/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Shipping: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received about possible revision of the seafarer's earnings deduction incentive.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","33411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509991","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-18","<p>The Government is carefully considering the responses received to the discussion paper on options to support English regional airports from the impacts of air passenger duty devolution and will respond in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The options contained in the discussion paper could each be taken forward in a variety of ways. Any proposals brought forward will be compliant with EU law and the European Commission will be consulted, if required.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-04-18T14:05:52.97Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509991/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509991/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509991/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to his Department's discussion paper on options for supporting English regional airports from the impacts of air passenger duty devolution, published in July 2015, what advice he has received from the European Commission on the compliance of the options in that paper with state aid rules; and whether he plans to issue an update to that discussion paper.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","33385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509992","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>Complete outturn figures, including receipts administered by public sector bodies and those received directly by beneficiaries, for the UK’s gross and net contribution to the EU Budget in 2014 can be found in Table 3B, page 16, of HM Treasury’s European Union Finances 2015 publication (Cm 9167) which is available from the House library and on gov.uk. No estimates are provided, as outturns for 2014 are available. The Government does not produce an estimate of the UK’s balance of payments with EU institutions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK’s contributions fluctuate between years. Over the years 2010 to 2014, the UK’s contributions averaged around £7.1bn. This means that for every pound paid in tax, a little over 1p goes to the EU. An explanation of these figures can be found in Annex B of HM Treasury’s analysis of the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-25T13:28:51.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509992/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509992/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","EU Institutions: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the Government's (a) gross and (b) net contribution  to EU institutions in 2014; and what the UK's balance of payments with those institutions was in that year.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","33432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509993","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) more than 26,000 (FTE) strong enforcement and compliance workforce of risk and intelligence analysts, compliance officers and fraud investigators tackle the full range of compliance risks ranging from hidden economy to the wealthy. Last year, they collected and protected a record £26 billion from compliance activities, contributing towards the UK's highest-ever tax take of £518 billion.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent year for which tax gap figures are available is 2013/14. HMRC estimates that £4.4 billion of it relates to tax evasion.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC allocates resources in a flexible manner, so that it meets individual business needs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has made additional resourcing of up to £10 million a year available for the creation of a new taskforce. Its purpose will be to swiftly obtain and analyse the Panama papers, and take rapid action where there is evidence of any wrongdoing and regulatory breaches. The taskforce will look beyond tax into all potential areas of financial crime and other regulatory breaches. It will be jointly led by HMRC and the National Crime Agency.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the structure and organisation of HMRC is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmrcs-annual-report-and-accounts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmrcs-annual-report-and-accounts</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-19T16:44:14.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509993/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509993/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509993/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Tax Evasion","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many employees of HM Revenue and Customs are employed to investigate tax evasion; what the estimated amount was of tax evasion in 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","33455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509994","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Government recognises the concerns raised around the Stamp Duty Land Tax (SDLT) treatment of self-contained annexes and agrees that the new higher rates of SDLT should not apply to a purchase of a main residence.</p><p>The Government is amending the Finance Bill to exempt annexes from the higher rates of SDLT when purchased in the same transaction as a main residence. In this case, the transaction will be treated as only involving one dwelling and SDLT at the standard rates will apply. An annex will be defined via objective criteria. It must be within the grounds of the main home and worth no more than a third of the total transaction value.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-14T13:29:14.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509994/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509994/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509994/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Stamp Duty Land Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether a self-contained annex to a house will be assessed separately from the entire residence for the purpose of calculating stamp duty at the point of sale; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","33441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509995","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-14","<p>The Government is currently conducting an evidence review into supported housing. We expect this review to conclude in the Spring.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-04-14T14:13:29.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509995/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509995/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509995/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential economic benefits of supported housing; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","33429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509996","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-19","<p>The taxation of UK companies operating in Malawi is governed by Malawian domestic tax law, where necessary modified by the terms of the UK/Malawi double taxation tax treaty. Negotiations between the two countries on a replacement treaty are substantially complete and the Malawian government has stated that it hopes to be in a position to sign the new treaty in the near future.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-19T16:33:11.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509996/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509996/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509996/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Overseas Companies: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to change the terms of tax conditions for UK multinational companies operating in Malawi.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","33467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509997","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-19","<p>It is for the local planning authority to determine what is required and seek planning obligations through a Section 106 agreement in order to make a development acceptable in planning terms. There are three statutory tests that need to be applied when considering a planning obligation, that it is: necessary to make the development acceptable in planning terms; directly related to the development; and fairly and reasonably related in scale and kind to the development.</p><p>Developers may be asked to provide contributions for infrastructure in several ways. This may be by way of planning obligations in the form of Section 106 agreements but can also include contributions through payment of the Community Infrastructure Levy and Section 278 highway agreements.</p><p>It is for local planning authorities to decide what provisions they make in Section 106 agreements, and agree these with the interested parties, and therefore any liabilities would depend on the individual agreement. Local authorities and developers can renegotiate planning obligations by mutual agreement at any time or under Section 106A of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990. However, Local planning authorities are expected to use all of the funding they receive through planning obligations in accordance with the terms of the individual planning obligation agreement. This is to ensure that new developments are acceptable in planning terms; benefit local communities and support the provision of local infrastructure.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","33437","2016-04-19T15:02:33.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509997/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509997/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Roads: Planning Obligations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, in the event that the actual cost of a Section 106 highway infrastructure scheme exceeds the previously estimated and agreed contribution, (a) what options exist for making good that shortfall, (b) whether the local authority or the developer is liable for any additional costs and (c) whether Section 106 contributions originally allocated for other schemes may be reallocated to cover such costs.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","33438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509998","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-19","<p>It is for the local planning authority to determine what is required and seek planning obligations through a Section 106 agreement in order to make a development acceptable in planning terms. There are three statutory tests that need to be applied when considering a planning obligation, that it is: necessary to make the development acceptable in planning terms; directly related to the development; and fairly and reasonably related in scale and kind to the development.</p><p>Developers may be asked to provide contributions for infrastructure in several ways. This may be by way of planning obligations in the form of Section 106 agreements but can also include contributions through payment of the Community Infrastructure Levy and Section 278 highway agreements.</p><p>It is for local planning authorities to decide what provisions they make in Section 106 agreements, and agree these with the interested parties, and therefore any liabilities would depend on the individual agreement. Local authorities and developers can renegotiate planning obligations by mutual agreement at any time or under Section 106A of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990. However, Local planning authorities are expected to use all of the funding they receive through planning obligations in accordance with the terms of the individual planning obligation agreement. This is to ensure that new developments are acceptable in planning terms; benefit local communities and support the provision of local infrastructure.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","33438","2016-04-19T15:02:33.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509998/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509998/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Roads: Planning Obligations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether Section 106 contributions for highways infrastructure works can be used to pay for (a) the costs of administrative, legal or design work or general highways maintenance works required prior to the installation of highways infrastructure works and (b) other associated overhead costs incurred by the local highways authority or its contractors.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","33437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509999","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-14","<p>Baroness Williams of Trafford replied on 12 April.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-04-14T15:35:16.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509999/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/509999/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he expects to reply to the letter of 7 March 2016 from the hon. Member for Walsall North concerning ESOL funding.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","33439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510000","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-14","<p>A written question for a named day was not replied to on time as a result of a clerical error within the departmental parliamentary team. A reply to the hon Member's letter of 17 February has been sent.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-04-14T15:36:01.053Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510000/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510000/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Department for Communities and Local Government: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reasons his Department did not answer Question 32050 from the hon. Member for Walsall North, tabled on 11 April 2016, or the letter sent to him on 17 February 2016; and if he will give an explanation why a written question for a named day was not replied to on time.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","33460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510001","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-19","<p>Section 106 agreements are negotiated and agreed between a local planning authority and a developer and/or landowner along with other interested parties in the land, such as mortgage providers. National planning policy makes clear that Section 106 requirements, modifications and discharges should be transparent and available for inspection.</p><p>Local planning authorities are expected to use all of the funding they receive through planning obligations in accordance with the terms of the individual planning obligation agreement. This is to ensure that new developments are acceptable in planning terms; benefit local communities and support the provision of local infrastructure.</p><p>Planning decisions should be based on Local Plan policy unless material considerations indicate otherwise. Representations from interested third parties may constitute material considerations. Town councils, parish councils and local communities can influence infrastructure and other considerations in Local Plans through the consultation process.</p><p>The Community Infrastructure Levy was introduced to provide a faster, fairer and more transparent approach to collecting developer contributions toward infrastructure. The Government launched a review of the Levy in 2015. This review will consider a range of issues, including the relationship between the Levy and Section 106 planning obligations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","33413 ; 33415","2016-04-19T15:06:27.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510001/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510001/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Roads: Planning Obligations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether regulations are in place to ensure that (a) town councils, (b) parish councils and (c) local communities have access to itemised expenditure on any associated administrative, legal, design, preparatory or maintenance works associated with individual highways infrastructure works within their areas on which Section 106 contributions have been spent.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","33414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510002","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-19","<p>Section 106 agreements are negotiated and agreed between a local planning authority and a developer and/or landowner along with other interested parties in the land, such as mortgage providers. National planning policy makes clear that Section 106 requirements, modifications and discharges should be transparent and available for inspection.</p><p>Local planning authorities are expected to use all of the funding they receive through planning obligations in accordance with the terms of the individual planning obligation agreement. This is to ensure that new developments are acceptable in planning terms; benefit local communities and support the provision of local infrastructure.</p><p>Planning decisions should be based on Local Plan policy unless material considerations indicate otherwise. Representations from interested third parties may constitute material considerations. Town councils, parish councils and local communities can influence infrastructure and other considerations in Local Plans through the consultation process.</p><p>The Community Infrastructure Levy was introduced to provide a faster, fairer and more transparent approach to collecting developer contributions toward infrastructure. The Government launched a review of the Levy in 2015. This review will consider a range of issues, including the relationship between the Levy and Section 106 planning obligations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","33413 ; 33414","2016-04-19T15:06:28.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510002/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510002/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Roads: Planning Obligations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether regulations are in place to ensure that (a) town councils, (b) parish councils and (c) local communities receive regular updates from highways authorities about (i) the sum total for Section 106 contributions for highways infrastructure works promised and delivered within their areas each year and (ii) a breakdown of expenditure on individual works within their areas.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","33415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510003","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-19","<p>Section 106 agreements are negotiated and agreed between a local planning authority and a developer and/or landowner along with other interested parties in the land, such as mortgage providers. National planning policy makes clear that Section 106 requirements, modifications and discharges should be transparent and available for inspection.</p><p>Local planning authorities are expected to use all of the funding they receive through planning obligations in accordance with the terms of the individual planning obligation agreement. This is to ensure that new developments are acceptable in planning terms; benefit local communities and support the provision of local infrastructure.</p><p>Planning decisions should be based on Local Plan policy unless material considerations indicate otherwise. Representations from interested third parties may constitute material considerations. Town councils, parish councils and local communities can influence infrastructure and other considerations in Local Plans through the consultation process.</p><p>The Community Infrastructure Levy was introduced to provide a faster, fairer and more transparent approach to collecting developer contributions toward infrastructure. The Government launched a review of the Levy in 2015. This review will consider a range of issues, including the relationship between the Levy and Section 106 planning obligations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","33414 ; 33415","2016-04-19T15:06:28.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510003/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510003/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Roads: Planning Obligations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what procedures are in place to ensure that (a) town councils, (b) parish councils and (c) local communities have the opportunity to influence how Section 106 contributions for highways infrastructure works are spent within their areas.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","33413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510004","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-26","<p>One person without a home is one too many and we are committed to do all we can to prevent homelessness. We announced at Budget an additional £100 million to deliver low cost ‘move on’ accommodation to enable people leaving hostels and refuges to make a sustainable recovery from a homelessness crisis, providing at least 2,000 places for vulnerable people to enable independent living.</p><p>The supported housing sector provides valuable support to some of our country’s most vulnerable people. It helps many people to lead independent lives or turn their lives around and is an investment which brings savings to other parts of the public sector – such as health and social care.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-04-26T15:18:06.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510004/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510004/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Sleeping Rough: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the potential benefits of supported housing in helping people to make the transition from rough sleeping back to independent living.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","33424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510005","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-19","<p>The number of a) resignations and b) proportion of officials resigning in my department in each of the last 6 years was as follows:</p><p>2010-11<br>a) 53<br>b) 2.7%</p><p>2011-12<br>a) 39<br>b) 2.1%</p><p>2012-13<br>a) 37<br>b) 2.1%</p><p>2013-14<br>a) 44<br>b) 2.6%</p><p>2014-15<br>a) 42<br>b) 2.5%</p><p>2015-16<br>a) 44<br>b) 2.6%</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-04-19T14:51:14.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510005/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510005/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Department for Communities and Local Government: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of officials of his Department resigned in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","33285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510006","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-14","<p>HM Treasury collects and publishes data on centrally supported PFI and PF2 (the UK Government’s main form of PPPs) projects. The most recent collection recorded projects as at 31<sup>st</sup> March 2015. This can be found at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/private-finance-initiative-and-private-finance-2-projects-2015-summary-data. This publication has the information requested on projects in the UK and Birmingham.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury does not hold information on ‘statutory actors’ in PFI and PF2 projects, however the published data does show the contracting parties, equity holders and special purpose vehicle responsible for managing the project.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-04-14T13:26:20.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510006/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510006/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-11","Public Private Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, in how many public private partnerships in (a) the UK and (b) Birmingham the Government is involved as a (i) party to the contract and (ii) statutory actor.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","33354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510007","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-19","<p>If the Housing Association is in England and registered with the Homes and Community Agency (HCA), they would have to ensure that they meet the regulatory Standards. However, the Secretary of State has no statutory power to intervene with under-performing Housing Associations.</p><p>If the Social Housing Regulator finds that a registered provider has failed to comply with the Standards, it has enforcement powers to ensure compliance with the standards.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-04-19T14:57:39.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510007/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510007/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Housing Associations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what powers he has to intervene with under-performing housing associations.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","33317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510008","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-21","<p>My Department has recently completed compliance testing of local authorities with the Local Government Transparency Code 2015, which entailed checking the websites of 103 authorities, a 25% sample of authorities to which the Transparency Code applies, for the data they are required to publish. We are currently analysing the initial results, including to ascertain whether where expected information has not been found on an authority’s website this is an accurate reflection of the authority’s circumstances or due to non-compliance.</p><p>Principal local authorities will not be required to comply with the provisions of the Local Audit and Accountability Act until 1 April 2018 [and Health and smaller bodies from 1 April 2017]. Compliance is currently monitored by Public Sector Audit Appointments Ltd, a transitional body appointed to manage existing audit arrangements until they expire.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","33341","2016-04-21T16:11:46.98Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510008/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510008/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/510008/answer/previousversion/55186","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-11","Local Government: Public Private Partnerships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2016 to Question 31226, how his Department monitors local authorities for compliance with their obligation under the (a) Local Audit and Accountability Act 2014 and (b) Local Government Transparency Code 2015.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","33342"
